    "preparations_description": "The main herbal preparations of Calamagrostis pallida are tea, infusion, tincture, salve, and decoction. These preparations are used to utilize the plant's medicinal properties, such as its anti-inflammatory and antioxidant effects, which are attributed to the presence of flavonoids, phenolic acids, and phenolic glycosides. To make a tea, the dried leaves are steeped in boiling water, while an infusion requires the leaves to be steeped in cold water, allowing the constituents to be extracted more slowly. A tincture is made by soaking the leaves in a solvent such as ethanol, resulting in a concentrated liquid extract. A decoction is prepared by boiling the dried roots and rhizomes, and a salve is made by infusing the plant material in oil to create a topical cream.",
